    <div class="page-header">
      <span class="severity-badge"><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i> Critical Severity | OWASP A08:2021</span>
      <h1>📌 PHP Object Injection (Insecure Deserialization)</h1>
    </div>
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>🧠 Description</h2>
      <p><strong>What is the vulnerability?</strong></p>
      <p>PHP Object Injection occurs when user‑supplied input is passed to <code>unserialize()</code> without proper validation. An attacker can supply a crafted serialized string that, when unserialized, instantiates arbitrary PHP objects and may trigger magic methods (e.g., <code>__wakeup()</code>, <code>__destruct()</code>) leading to Remote Code Execution (RCE), file deletion, or privilege escalation.</p>
      <p><strong>Why does it occur?</strong></p>
      <p>Developers use <code>unserialize()</code> on data from cookies, session storage, or API inputs, trusting it without sanitisation.</p>
      <p><strong>Security principle violated:</strong> Insecure Deserialization</p>
      <p><strong>Real-world analogy:</strong> Accepting a pre‑packaged box from a stranger and opening it – you have no control over what's inside.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>🏷️ Classification</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Type:</strong> Insecure Deserialization</li>
        <li><strong>OWASP:</strong> A08:2021 – Software and Data Integrity Failures</li>
        <li><strong>CWE:</strong> CWE-502: Deserialization of Untrusted Data</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>🎯 Attack Surface</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>✅ PHP sessions (serialized data in cookies or files)</li>
        <li>✅ API endpoints accepting serialized objects (e.g., <code>application/x-php-serialized</code>)</li>
        <li>✅ Parameters passed to <code>unserialize()</code> from user input</li>
        <li>✅ Applications using <code>__wakeup()</code> or <code>__destruct()</code> for file operations</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>🔍 Detection Methodology</h2>
      <h3>1. Static Analysis</h3>
      <div class="code-block"><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</button>
        <pre>// Look for unserialize() with user input
$data = unserialize($_GET['data']);</pre>
      </div>
      <h3>2. Dynamic Analysis</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Look for parameters that look like serialized PHP data: <code>O:4:"User":1:{s:4:"name";s:3:"abc";}</code></li>
        <li>Fuzz with a harmless serialized object and observe behaviour changes.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>💣 Basic Payloads</h2>
      <div class="code-block"><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</button>
        <pre># Simple serialized string for a class with a destructor
O:1:"A":0:{}</pre>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>🚀 Advanced Exploitation (POP Chain)</h2>
      <div class="code-block"><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</button>
        <pre># Example payload using a known gadget chain (PHPGGC)
phpggc Monolog/RCE1 system 'id' -s
# Then send the generated payload to the vulnerable unserialize() endpoint.</pre>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>🧪 Test Cases (STRICT)</h2>
      <table class="test-cases">
        <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Action</th><th>Expected</th><th>Actual</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.75rem;">1</td><td style="padding: 0.75rem;">Submit a malformed serialized string (e.g., <code>O:1:"A":0:{}</code>)</td><td style="padding: 0.75rem;">Error or no effect</td><td style="padding: 0.75rem;">Application crash or unexpected behaviour</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.75rem;">2</td><td style="padding: 0.75rem;">Use PHPGGC to generate a payload for RCE</td><td style="padding: 0.75rem;">No output or blocked</td><td style="padding: 0.75rem;">Command executed (e.g., <code>id</code> output)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>✔ Must be reproducible</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>⚙️ Exploitation Steps</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Identify input that is passed to <code>unserialize()</code>.</li>
        <li>Enumerate classes and available magic methods (use code review or PHPGGC).</li>
        <li>Craft a gadget chain to achieve RCE.</li>
        <li>Deliver the payload and execute commands.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>🛡️ Mitigation</h2>
      <div class="mitigation-box">
        <strong>✅ Never use <code>unserialize()</code> on user input.</strong><br>
        <strong>✅ Use safe alternatives like <code>json_decode()</code>.</strong><br>
        <strong>✅ Implement allowlist of classes when deserializing (e.g., <code>unserialize($data, ['allowed_classes' => ['MyClass']])</code>).</strong><br>
        <strong>✅ Use signature verification (HMAC) for serialized data.</strong><br>
        <strong>✅ Keep dependencies updated to avoid known gadget chains.</strong>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>🔓 Mitigation Bypass</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>If allowlist is too broad, attackers may still find usable classes.</li>
        <li>If custom autoloaders are misconfigured, new classes can be injected.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>⚠️ Risk / Impact</h2>
      <div class="vulnerability-box">
        <strong>Severity: Critical</strong><br><br>
        <strong>Impact:</strong> Remote Code Execution, complete server takeover, data breach.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="content-section">
      <h2>📎 Proof of Concept (PoC)</h2>
      <div class="code-block"><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy</button>
        <pre># Vulnerable code
$data = $_GET['data'];
$obj = unserialize($data);

# Payload
?data=O:8:"stdClass":0:{}</pre>
      </div>
    </div>
